    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:2b6dbd77-57a2-4ee3-afbd-062852a7d852",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is an energetic 8-year-old boy with a mop of dark brown hair and bright hazel eyes, currently looking a bit under the weather. He attends second grade at a local elementary school, where he is known for his enthusiasm in art class and his love of soccer during recess. He lives at home with his parents and a younger sister. His after-school routine usually involves football practice in the backyard and playing video games with his best friend next door.\n\nAt presentation, {patientName} appears mildly ill but alert and interactive. He has a runny nose with clear-to-slightly-yellow nasal discharge, red and watery eyes, and visible nasal congestion that makes him breathe through his mouth. He has been sneezing frequently and complaining of a scratchy, sore throat. His voice sounds slightly nasal and hoarse.\n\nHis mother reports that symptoms began approximately three days ago, starting with mild sneezing and a tickle in his throat, then progressing to a full nasal congestion and a mild cough that is worse at night. He has been slightly feverish, sleeping more than usual, and refusing some meals, though he continues to drink fluids adequately.\n\n{patientName} is generally an active and healthy child who enjoys outdoor play, especially when his neighborhood friends are around. He has never smoked (as expected for his age) and has no significant dietary restrictions. He attends a classroom with 24 other children, and his teacher recently noted that several classmates have had similar cold-like symptoms in the past week.\n\nHis parents describe him as a cheerful and cooperative boy, though he has been unusually irritable and clingy since becoming ill. He loves dinosaurs, superhero cartoons, and is learning to ride a bicycle. His father works as a school bus driver and his mother is a part-time librarian."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:63197549-fe36-4b78-9ffd-2ed33f8a818a",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
